minimum standards of safety and the ability to teach among parents who homeschool. &#10;Also, children educated at home could be easily cut off from the rest of society, and wouldn't necessarily have anyone to notice if they were bruised, or acting strangely, or displaying signs of abuse. I think it's right that the state should have the right to ask children whether they are being abused - I don't understand why you disagree. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="730" language="en" documentId="869" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Covenant" date="06 November 2009 2:32pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6743177" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="9" thumbsDown="0" origId="869" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="194"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="195" end="386"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="387" end="730"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>